I’ve done it.") (h2 ((id . "p-1")) "So What’s the Problem?") (p nil "One thing I hear over and over, when I’m talking to RPs, is “How do I force
re-authentication?”  A bit of background is in order. The way being an RP works
is that you do a browser redirect over to the IDP, in effect asking “Is this
the person they say they are?”
If you do this with Facebook or Google or whoever, and if
the person is already logged in via that browser, most times the IDP will just
come back and say “Yep, they’re authenticated” without pestering the user.") (p nil "But some RPs want to make the IDP re-authenticate, that is to say make the
person at the browser type in a password and maybe do the 2-factor thing too.
Because they’re about to do something really meaningful, involving money or
privacy or whatever.
For example, I was recently talking to some people from a well-known newspaper
that wanted to force re-auth when their journalists accessed the internal
publishing system from outside the firewall.") (h2 ((id . "p-3")) "Why Is That a Problem?") (p nil "Well, one of the key advantages Federated Identity is cutting down the
number of times people have to type in passwords. There are a bunch of good
reasons for this:") (ul nil (li nil (p nil "Every time it happens, that’s another chance for password
theft.")) (li nil (p nil "We don’t want to get people into the habit of typing IDP passwords in
here and there; that habit is a great big red target sign saying “Phish
me!”")) (li nil (p nil "Typing passwords all the time is a painful user experience,
particularly on mobile devices.")) (li nil (p nil "The easiest way to reduce that pain is to use a short, simple,
